{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ef8453a0-ddf8-4072-b5b1-aaeaf47ce2ce","content":"## The Issue\n\n.NET MAUI's Android workload **ships with its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17**. When your `JAVA_HOME` points to a different distribution (Adoptium Temurin), the build picks up that JDK instead, which can cause compatibility issues with the Android build tooling.\n\n## The Fix\n\n**Option A — Let .NET use its bundled JDK (recommended):**\n\nUnset `JAVA_HOME` before building, or remove it from your shell profile:\n\n```bash\nunset JAVA_HOME\ndotnet build\n```\n\n.NET will automatically find its bundled Microsoft OpenJDK at:\n`~/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/microsoft_dist_serverJRE_17.*/`\n\n**Option B — Point to the bundled JDK explicitly in your `.csproj`:**\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>$(HOME)/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Option C — If you must keep Temurin**, tell MSBuild to use it explicitly so both systems agree:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>$(JAVA_HOME)</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nOption A is the simplest — just unset `JAVA_HOME` and let the .NET workload manage Java for you.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"802a67a9-7b9f-44d0-b1f2-f438b2dae811","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what the common issue is here.\n\nThe common issue with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java is that .NET MAUI / Xamarin.Android requires a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, the Android SDK requires JDK 17, but there can be issues with certain JDK distributions or versions.\n\nHowever, a very common problem on macOS specifically is that the `JAVA_HOME` path needs to point to the correct location. On macOS with Adoptium Temurin, the JDK is typically installed at `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`.\n \n.NET MAUI bundles its own JDK and sometimes conflicts with externally installed versions, though the real issue here might be that specific minor versions of JDK 17 have compatibility problems with the Android toolchain on macOS. the Microsoft OpenJDK distribution, and the build system may not recognize Adoptium Temurin properly.\n\nActually, the most likely issue is simpler than that. The .NET Android workload ships with its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17, and `JAVA_HOME` pointing to a different JDK can cause conflicts. The fix is typically to either unset `JAVA_HOME` and let the .NET build system use its bundled JDK, or set it to the Microsoft OpenJDK that comes with the workload.\n\nThe user hasn't specified the exact error, so I'm thinking through the most common Java-related MAUI build failures: JDK version mismatches, distribution incompatibilities, incorrect `JAVA_HOME` paths on macOS, or Gradle/aapt2 issues. Since they have JDK 17, the version should be fine for .NET 8 MAUI, but on macOS there's often a conflict when `JAVA_HOME` points to an external JDK while the .NET build tries to use its bundled one. The practical solution is either letting MAUI use its bundled Microsoft OpenJDK by unsetting `JAVA_HOME`, or explicitly configuring the Android build to use Temurin through the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property. The real issue is that .NET MAUI includes its own bundled Microsoft OpenJDK, and pointing `JAVA_HOME` to Adoptium Temurin instead creates conflicts during the build process—the solution is to either let .NET use its included JDK or explicitly configure the project to use the correct one.","outputTokens":1387},"id":"ecc9be54-ed0d-4a96-b363-7054b07b9414","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:49:48.994Z","parentId":"53647016-792d-4278-8ea9-ebf65033a1ec"}
